<h1>To John Hancock</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">New York April 30. 1776.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I mean thro you Sir to do myself the Honor of laying before Congress, a Copy of an Address transmitted them some time agoe by the Assembly of Rhode Island, which Governor Cooke favoured me with in the month of January, at the same time requesting me to Interest myself in procuring a body of forces on the Continental establishment for the defence of that Colony.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I doubt not but the Address &amp; Subject of It, have had the Attention and consideration of Congress before now, but If they have not decided upon the matter, I woud beg leave to mention that I have made enquiry into the situation &amp; condition of this Colony and find It to be, as Stated in the address, and with all deference to the opinion of Congress, conceive It highly necessary and expedient that they shoud adopt some measures for relieving their distress and granting the aid prayed for. The importance of It in the Chain of union, Its extensive Sea Coast affording Harbours for our Shipping &amp; Vessels, at the same time exposing &amp; Subjecting the Inhabitants to the ravages &amp; depredations of our Enemies; the zeal &amp; attachment which It has shewn &amp; which still actuates It toward the Common cause, the incapacity to pay a sufficient number of men for Its defence, shoud they be able to furnish em after so many engaged in other Services, these and many other reasons, which are too obvious to be mentioned, plead powerfully for the notice and attention of Congress &amp; seem to me to claim their Support. Having thus stated the matter to Congress for their consideration agreable to my promise to Governor Cooke when I had the honor of seeing him in my way here, I shall leave It with them, not doubting but they will duly weigh Its importance &amp; give such assistance as they may think reasonable &amp; Just; what they chiefly wish for is, that the Troops they have raised may be taken into Continental pay &amp; a Commanding Officer to be appointed by Congress.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> I have the honor to be with much regard Sir Yr Most H. Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0176">[176]</span>
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0141-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, in Robert Hanson Harrisons writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 152; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 169; 
copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC</span>: Hancock Papers; 
copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Record Group (designating the location of documents in the National Archives) ]">RG</span> 93, Miscellaneous Numbered Records (Manuscript File), 177584, no. 15644; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 Congress read this letter on 2 May (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:322).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0111" class="document">Nicholas Cooke to GW, 21 Jan.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0094" class="document">23 April</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0127" class="document">GW to Cooke, 28 April 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0141-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Congress resolved on 11 May to take into Continental pay two regiments that the Rhode Island general assembly had ordered to be raised (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:347). GWs letter to Hancock, as Stephen Hopkins informed Cooke on 15 May, greatly influenced Congress to pass that resolution. I could therefore wish, Hopkins wrote, the Colony in a handsome manner to acknowledge this favour and to return thanks to the General for his good offices in their behalf (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Paul H. Smith et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Letters of Delegates to Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;. 26 vols. Washington, D.C., 19762000. ]">Smith, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Delegates</span></span>, 3:68182). For Rhode Islands thanks, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0180" class="document">Cooke to GW, 6 May</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-05-02-0028" class="document">20 June 1776</a>; see also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0225" class="document">GW to Cooke, 13 May 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
